defaultAFS0090defaultWritten Evidencedefault defaultsubmitted by the defaultIAAdefaultThe IAA (Independent Academies Association) 
defaultis 
defaultthe national membership organisation for leaders of academies. 
default 
defaultWe are a non-partisan representative organisation committed to supporting our members in the advancement of the education and life chances of all pupils and students in our care. 
default 
defaultAn acknowledged and respected national body, we are ‘the voice of academies’
default, run by and on behalf of our continually growing membership. We play a leading role in the development of the wider academy movement, providing help, support and advice to existing, new and converting academies. 
default 
defaultWe are the only independent organisation d
defaultedicated to supporting academies and have a track record of over 20 years’ experience in providing leadership to all types of state-funded independent schools.
default 
default 
defaultOur work includes lobbying 
defaultgovernment and opposition on matters relating to education policy
default as
default it affects academies.
default2.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe IAA (Independent Academies Association
default) firmly believes that the overarching principle and foremost priority of the academies 
defaultmovement
default is the urgent need to deliver high quality education to all students and pupils.  
default2.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultEvidential data demonstrates that the 
defaultacademies 
defaultprogramme has been effective in 
defaultraising standards
default, with the impact being greatest among sponsored academies
default.
default 
default2.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultMore could be 
defaultdone to incentivise increased numbers of good and outstanding converter academies to sponsor failing schools, particularly those that predominantly serve disadvantaged children.
default2.4.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe 
defaultaccelerated pace of
default academisation
default has caused some issues, most notably in 
defaultthe variable quality of sponsors and governing bodies.
default 
defaultWhen problems occur in this area, they must be resolved more quickly than hitherto. Further reform of 
defaultschool 
defaultgovernance
default 
defaultis recommended.
default2.5.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAny temptation to reinvent the ‘middle tier’ along 
defaultprevious 
defaultlocal
default authority lines should be 
defaultresisted
default: instead, greater impetus should be provided to system leadership 
defaulton a sub-regional basis 
defaultas part of a truly self-improving system.
default2.6.
default&#xa0; 
defaultLocal authorities 
defaultcould
default continue to 
defaulthave strategic and statutory roles to play but they 
defaultmust not be at the expense of academy independence or autonomy.
default2.7.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe IAA welcomes the introduction of sub-regional Schools Commissioners and Headteacher Boards as a proportionate response to 
defaultthe ongoing expansion of the academies programme
default.
default2.8.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAcademy chains have a crucial role to play in the new educational landscape, with 
defaultmany demonstrating outstanding ability to transform education
default.   
default2.9.
default&#xa0; 
defaultAcademy status is equally relevant to primary schools as it is to secondary schools and growth in the number
defaults of primary academies should be supported and encouraged.
default&#xa0;
default3.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIn 2010, the NAO noted that, o
defaultverall, academies 
defaultincrease
default the rate of improvement in GCSE results when compared wi
defaultth their predecessor schools. 
default Furthermore
default, the proportion of 
defaultacademy students
default achieving five or more A*-C 
defaultat GCSE
default 
defaulthad
default improved
default at a faster rate than in maintained schools
default, particularly those
default with similar intakes
default.
default  
defaultIn 2011 and 2012 schools with academy st
defaultatus made, on average, more progress between KS2 and GCSE than schools without academy status
default.
default3.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThose sponsored academies
default that were established early on in the programme replaced the worst schools in the country and, in nearly every case, transformed provision and dramatically and very rapidly improved outcomes. The focus was on removing 
defaultfrom the system 
defaultthe rump of the 200 
defaultl
defaultowest
default performing schools
default, where underperformance was historically endemic and stubbornly ingrained and which were situated in some of the most disadvantaged and challenged areas of the UK. 
default3.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe fact that the early academy sponsors turned around these schoo
defaultls in the most 
defaultdifficult
default of circumstances, with few very failures, is testament to the efficacy of the programme and it is, therefore, no surprise that we have recently witnessed 
defaulta 
defaultresurgence in this approach
default, which is welcomed by our association.
default3.4.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIt can also be no accident that the 
defaultsuccess of initiatives such as London Challenge was
default contemporaneous with
default a period of mass academisation of schools within the area.
default3.5.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe most compelling evidence for the effectiveness of academies has come in the recently
default published Ofsted Annual Report, which notes that: 
defaultSponsor-led academies are delivering a step change in performance for chronically
default underperforming schools. Academies established in 2007 have narrowed the attainment gap of five or 
defaultmore A* to C grades at 
defaultGCSE, including English and 
defaultmathematics, by eight percentage points.
default 
default3.6.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe report also goes on to state that “
defaultAcademy converters are outperforming all non-academy schools” and that “Sponsor-led academies that have been open since 2007 have made the most im
defaultprovement at Key Stage 4”, suggesting that the longer an academy is established, the greater its impact
default over time
default.
