default4.1.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe IAA acknowledges
default and welcomes the moves made by Ministers in recent times to increase the rigour in selecting academy sponsors / free school proposers, in assessing the capacity of existing sponsors to take on additional academies
default,
default and in pausing or halting the expansion 
defaultof chains where there have been concerns about academic performance or financial management.
default 
default4.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultHowever
default, the process 
defaultleading to
default ministerial approval and subsequent academisation remains unwieldy and can be painfully slow
default,
default not only for the prospective sponsor
default but for the children attending 
defaultfailing schools, their parents 
defaultand 
defaultthe 
defaultstaff working in
default them
default.
default 
default Schools can find themselves in a protracted state of limbo, where uncertainty and the inability to move forward can impact detrimentally on stakeholder confidenc
defaulte, the quality of provision and sometimes on outcomes.
default4.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulthe DfE might usefully consider further refinements to the two approaches to academisation, the so-called ‘fast-track’ and ‘fully sponsored’ routes, which are rightly based on assessments of potential 
defaultrisk, in order to ensure that, where necessary, children’s education can be transformed without delay. 
default4.4.
default&#xa0; 
defaultWith regard to the programme as a whole, however, in some ways the converse is true, as t
defaulthe 
defaultaccelerated pace of
default academisation
default has caused some issues, mo
defaultst notably in the variable quality of sponsors and governing bodies.
default 
default4.5.
default&#xa0; 
defaultWhen problems occur in this area, they must be resolved more 
defaultreadily
default than hitherto. 
defaultThe Department should act more quickly to reassign a sponsor/trust where a mistake has been made
default.
default4.6.
default&#xa0; 
defaultExisting governing bodies of schools rated less than good by Ofsted should not be involved in choos
defaulting their own academy sponsor. 
defaultIt is appropriate that, where a local authority has worked closely with a school and knows it well, they should have a voice i
defaultn respect of the choice of sponsor but the local authority should not have any power of veto.  
default4.7.
default&#xa0; 
defaultWe acknowledge that there is less “soft sponsorship” of schools than was the case at one time, but more can still be done and similar ‘tightening up’ may be nee
defaultded in the free schools programme. 
default4.8.
default&#xa0; 
defaultTo support sponsor selection and to ensure rigorous accountability, we
default need a transparent, easy to access register of sponsors 
defaultthat
default for each sponsor
default includes
default:
default a list of schools they run
default;
default the
default Ofsted
default judgments of each of t
defaulthose schools
default;
default and
default the
default improvement
defaults in progress and attainment that have
default been achieved
default.
default 
default4.9.
default&#xa0; 
defaultFurther reform of 
defaultschool 
defaultgovernance, 
defaultfor example
default to align it more with
default the most successful practice in
default the business sector, is recommended
default, 
defaultwith 
defaultvery clear and transpar
defaultent accountability, 
defaultmuch smaller boards of non-executive directors, fewer committees and more performance management of governors than is currently the case in the majority of schools and academies.  Within a group setting, the role of the Executive Princi
defaultpal / Chief Executive Officer with regard to governance should be more clearly defined and emphasised, as should that of other Executive Directors.  I
defaultt may be that radical 
defaulttransformation
default 
defaultof governance 
defaultis required in order to help bring about the next step 
defaultchange in the education system as a whole
default.
