default6.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultClarit
defaulty is needed regarding the duties of local authorities with regard to education, which should be limited to a narrow set of statutory functions, e.g. safeguarding children, admissions and special educational needs.
default 
default I
defaultt is important that all statutory servic
defaultes that local authorities provide are of high quality
default. 
default6.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultHowever, any local authority powers, including 
defaultany
default that 
defaultmay 
defaultrelate to promoting high standards in schools, should not impinge on academy independence or autonomy: to do so would undermine a fundamenta
defaultl premise of the academies movement, namely that with greater freedoms come greater responsibilities. 
default6.4.
default&#xa0; 
defaultWithin this context, it is inappropriate for local authorities or, indeed, the Department for Education (DfE) to have a role in ‘supporting’ academies an
defaultd free schools. It is far more fitting and sustainable in the long term to seek to promote a self-improving system
default where the very best practitioners are always 
defaultoutward looking
default and help others to improve rapidly through a school-to-school model.
default 
default6.5.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe IAA we
defaultlcomes recent statements from Ministers and officials regarding the intention to regionalise more of the DfE’s work and to devolve certain functions and powers to sub-regional Schools Commissioners and Headteacher Boards.  It is wholly appropriate to 
defaultmake 
defaultmore use of 
defaultsuccessful 
defaultsystem leaders 
defaultin this way and to exploit the local knowledge of those closer to the chalk face than officials in Whitehall
default by devolving as many powers as possible
default.
default  
default6.6.
default&#xa0; 
defaultIf, as has been suggested, these new bodies are to be responsible 
defaultfor the early identification of underperformance and for brokering improvement and/or structural solutions, then they should also carry overarching duties in respect of overall performance within their sub-regions. 
